# Patch 0003: Parcel kHeader build-flag selectable for Westlake
# ==============================================================
#
# Why this patch exists
# ---------------------
# AOSP's Parcel.cpp picks a 4-byte "header magic" that gets written on every
# kernel-binder transaction payload. The kernel doesn't care about the value,
# but the peer libbinder's `Parcel::readInterfaceToken()` does — a mismatch
# is rejected as `BR_FAILED_REPLY` and the call dies.
#
# AOSP picks the header based on which __ANDROID_* macros are defined:
#
#   __ANDROID_VNDK__       -> 'VNDR'   (vendor partition processes)
#   __ANDROID_RECOVERY__   -> 'RECO'   (recovery boot mode)
#   __ANDROID__ (plain)    -> 'SYST'   (system partition processes)
#   (none of the above)    -> 'UNKN'   (default for non-Android builds)
#
# Westlake's libbinder is the non-Android case (we build with -U__ANDROID__
# even on the bionic variant so the source goes through the "host" code path,
# avoiding vintf/perfetto/SELinux dependencies we don't have). The vanilla
# 'UNKN' header would not interoperate with anything real — neither the
# OnePlus 6's system_server peers (which expect 'SYST') nor a stock OHOS
# vendor binder endpoint (which expects 'VNDR' on /dev/vndbinder).
#
# Resolution: make the choice selectable at compile time. The Makefile passes
# `-DWESTLAKE_KHEADER_SYST=1` for both the musl and the bionic build variants
# today (Phase 1 — talks to phone's Android system servicemanager and our own
# AOSP servicemanager registered as a SYST peer). Phase 2 can flip to
# `-DWESTLAKE_KHEADER_VNDR=1` for OHOS production deployments where libbinder
# needs to interoperate with OHOS-vendor binder endpoints. If neither flag
# is defined, the AOSP default ('UNKN') is preserved.
#
# Codex review (Tier 4, CR6): the original patch hardcoded 'SYST' which
# broke the "AOSP default behavior is unchanged when our defines aren't set"
# invariant and made any future stock-OHOS-vendor interop a fresh patch. The
# conditional below restores the AOSP default and gates Westlake behavior on
# explicit opt-in via the build flag.
#
# Build-flag reference
# --------------------
#   -DWESTLAKE_KHEADER_SYST=1   -> 'SYST'  (Phase 1 sandbox; this is what
#                                            today's Makefile sets)
#   -DWESTLAKE_KHEADER_VNDR=1   -> 'VNDR'  (Phase 2 stock-OHOS interop)
#   (neither defined)          -> 'UNKN'   (AOSP default, unmodified)
#
# Defining both at once is undefined-behavior on our side: the #if defined
# ladder picks SYST and silently drops VNDR. The Makefile sets exactly one.

--- /home/dspfac/aosp-sources/frameworks-native/libs/binder/Parcel.cpp	2026-05-12 11:39:03.350983832 -0700
+++ aosp-src/libbinder/Parcel.cpp	2026-05-12 17:30:00.000000000 -0700
@@ -956,9 +956,30 @@

 #else // ANDROID not defined

-// If kernel binder is used in new environments, we need to make sure it's
-// separated out and has a separate header.
-constexpr int32_t kHeader = B_PACK_CHARS('U', 'N', 'K', 'N');
+// libbinder-port: when libbinder runs on a non-__ANDROID__ host (OHOS musl
+// build, or our bionic build with -U__ANDROID__), AOSP defaults the header
+// to 'UNKN'.  That value gets rejected as BR_FAILED_REPLY by both the host
+// phone's Android system servicemanager (which expects 'SYST' on transaction
+// payloads) AND by a stock OHOS-vendor binder peer (which expects 'VNDR').
+// Pick the right one at compile time via the build flag:
+//
+//   -DWESTLAKE_KHEADER_SYST=1   -> 'SYST' (Phase 1 sandbox; talks to phone's
+//                                   system_server peers and our own SM)
+//   -DWESTLAKE_KHEADER_VNDR=1   -> 'VNDR' (future Phase 2 production OHOS,
+//                                   when libbinder must interoperate with
+//                                   stock OHOS-vendor binder endpoints)
+//   (neither defined)          -> 'UNKN' (AOSP default — unmodified behavior)
+//
+// Westlake builds always set WESTLAKE_KHEADER_SYST=1 today (see Makefile).
+#if defined(WESTLAKE_KHEADER_SYST)
+constexpr int32_t kHeader = B_PACK_CHARS('S', 'Y', 'S', 'T');
+#elif defined(WESTLAKE_KHEADER_VNDR)
+constexpr int32_t kHeader = B_PACK_CHARS('V', 'N', 'D', 'R');
+#else
+// If kernel binder is used in new environments, we need to make sure it's
+// separated out and has a separate header.
+constexpr int32_t kHeader = B_PACK_CHARS('U', 'N', 'K', 'N');
+#endif
 #endif

 #endif // BINDER_WITH_KERNEL_IPC
